# preprocessing the data
df['Time spent on TV'].replace('No tv', 0, inplace=True)
df['Time spent on TV'].replace('n', 0, inplace=True)
df['Time spent on TV'].replace('N', 0, inplace=True)
df['Time spent on TV'].replace(' ', 0, inplace=True)
df['Time spent on TV'] = df['Time spent on TV'].astype('float')
df['Prefered social media platform'] = df['Prefered social media platform'].replace('None ', 'None')
df['Prefered social media platform'] = df['Prefered social media platform'].replace('Whatsapp', 'WhatsApp')

# 8.Online Class Ratings 
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming your data is stored in a DataFrame called 'df'
# If not, replace 'df' with the actual name of your DataFrame

# Sample Data (Replace this with your actual DataFrame)
data = {
    'Rating_of_Online_Class_experience': ['Good', 'Excellent', 'Very poor', 'Very poor', 'Good', 'Very poor', 'Very poor', 'Very poor', 'Very poor', 'Very poor', 'Good', 'Very poor', 'Average', 'Good', 'Very poor', 'Average', 'Good', 'Very poor', 'Very poor', 'Very poor', 'Excellent']
}

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Countplot for online class ratings
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.countplot(x='Rating_of_Online_Class_experience', data=df, palette='viridis')

# Adding labels and title
plt.title('Distribution of Online Class Ratings')
plt.xlabel('Rating of Online Class Experience')
plt.ylabel('Count')

# Display the plot
plt.show()

# 9.A bar chart depicting the reported change in weight during the lockdown.
# Your dataset
data = {
    'ID': ['R1', 'R2', 'R3', 'R4', 'R5', 'R6', 'R7', 'R8', 'R9', 'R10', 'R11', 'R12', 'R13', 'R14', 'R15', 'R16', 'R17', 'R18', 'R19', 'R20', 'R21', 'R22', 'R23'],
    'Change_in_Weight': ['Increased', 'Decreased', 'Decreased', 'Decreased', 'Increased', 'Decreased', 'Increased', 'Increased', 'Increased', 'Decreased', 'Remain Constant', 'Increased', 'Increased', 'Increased', 'Remain Constant', 'Increased', 'Increased', 'Remain Constant', 'Increased', 'Increased', 'Decreased', 'Decreased', 'Increased']
}

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Count the occurrences of each change in weight category
weight_change_counts = df['Change_in_Weight'].value_counts()

# Plotting the bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
weight_change_counts.plot(kind='bar', color='skyblue')
plt.title('Reported Change in Weight During Lockdown')
plt.xlabel('Change in Weight')
plt.ylabel('Number of Participants')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.show()
